General Regression Strategy

  • Collect appropriate data
  • Identify Outcomes / predictors
  • Investigate “shape” of data
  • Consider appropriate functional form
  • Apply prior knowledge
  • Select “best” model and variables
  • Check model for validity (residuals, etc)
  • Apply model
  • Predict new results
  • R has great functionality for all of this

Regression Strategy from a Bayesian Perspective

  • Collect data
  • Perform EDA
  • Decide on a model (specify distribution for outcome and the parameters in the model)
  • Decide on priors for any parameters
  • Estimate the posterior using MCMC
  • Evaluate your model fit and consider other models
  • Summarize the model results by drawing from the posterior (predict new results)

OLS Regression (Linear Regression)

  • “Basic” regression
  • Easy to learn conceptually, applies to other
  • Outcome is a continuous variable
  • Predicting weight
  • Predicting monetary values
  • Predicting Lab tests
  • What are the assumptions of ordinary linear regression?

General Linear Model

  • The OLS linear model is actually type of general linear model (the simplest type). The general linear model framework with an identify link (more on this later) looks like this:

\[ \text{Y}_i \sim \text{Normal}(\eta, \sigma^2) \]

\[\eta = \beta _0 + \beta _1 X_1 + \beta _2 X_2...\beta _i X_i \]

-And the normal distribution is defined by:

\[ f(x \mid \mu, \sigma^2) = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2\pi\sigma^2}}e^{-\frac{(x-\mu)^2}{2\sigma^2}} \]

  • If the outcome is continuous, this is usually one of the first models we would consider.

Assumptions of OLS Regression

  • Assumptions this is key
  • Normality
  • Independence
  • Linearity
  • Homoscedasticity (pull this off in scrabble)

Formulas in R

  • We can express these models via formulas in R, using something like the following:

model <- lm(formula, data)

  • Formula is a special object in R

response variable ~ explanatory variable(s)

Y ~ X1 + X2 + X3 + X4...

Formula syntax

op description
+ + x include this variable
- - x delete this variable
: x:z include interaction
* x*z include interaction and lower
I I(x*z) Resolve expression before model
1 - 1 intercept: delete the intercept

Let’s fit our first model…

  • Let’s fit a basic model on the CO2 data. We will pretend we do not know the data generating process, then fit models accordingly and test to see how well they fit.

  • The first model we fit should be a ‘null’ model, or just the overall mean.

# Set some modeling parameters
library(rstanarm)
CHAINS = 4
SEED = 42

# Calculate overall mean
mean(CO2$uptake)
## [1] 27.2131
# Fit basic model, specifying priors
fit0 <- stan_glm(uptake ~ 1, 
                data = CO2,
                prior_intercept = normal(location = mean(CO2$uptake), 
                                         scale = 4, 
                                         autoscale = T),
                prior_aux = exponential(rate = 1,
                                        autoscale = T),
                chains=CHAINS,
                seed=SEED)

Interpreting the output of this model

  • We have estimated the null model, which essentially just means we estimated the mean of the distribution. This is likely a good estimate of the overall mean, but we can do better than this! (assuming there is some predictive power to be gained from the predictors)

  • Recall we can summarize the posterior predictions easily with some code like this:

# Mean of the posterior
mean(as.data.frame(fit0)$`(Intercept)`)
## [1] 27.22994
# Median
median(as.data.frame(fit0)$`(Intercept)`)
## [1] 27.25154
# same as the coef (median)
coef(fit0)
## (Intercept) 
##    27.25154
  • We can also ask about probabilities of the posterior distribution in the usual manner:
# probability that sample mean is less than 25
sum(as.data.frame(fit0)$`(Intercept)`<25) / length(as.data.frame(fit0)$`(Intercept)`)
## [1] 0.03625

How good is this model?

  • let’s take a few moments to review the output and talk through the summary statistics.
  • The sample size is the number of samples (post warm up)
  • The table of estimates is a standard table summarizing the posterior for each estimate
  • The fit diagnostic reported here is the mean_PPD. This is the mean of the posterior distribution. Ideally this will be close to the sample mean!
  • The MCMC diagnostics summarize how well the MCMC algorithm worked / converged. We will cover this in more depth later.

  • This all looks good! Convergence worked. However, does that mean we have a good model? Let’s investigate the posterior predictions (subject level) and compare that distribution to the actual data distribution.
library(bayesplot)
# examine the predicted values
posterior_predictions <- 
  posterior_predict(fit0) # don't need predictors for null model
# one column for each observation (84), one row for each chain element (4000)
str(posterior_predictions)
##  'ppd' num [1:4000, 1:84] 27.3 41.5 28.1 21.4 21 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ : NULL
##   ..$ : chr [1:84] "1" "2" "3" "4" ...
# Plotting function from bayesplot to examine the outcomes
ppc_dens(y = CO2$uptake,
         yrep = posterior_predictions[1:5,])

# Overlay multiple densities (first 100) - doing all of them takes awhile
ppc_dens_overlay(y = CO2$uptake,
         yrep = posterior_predictions[1:100,])

  • What do you think of the observed Y compared to the posterior Y reps?
  • It looks like the observed Y is bi-modal, but we are not getting that same behavior in the y reps (simulations from the posterior). This implies the specified model does not do a good job of describing the underlying population.
  • Interestingly, we are still effectively estimating the mean (because of the central limit theorem!). But this is a good indicator that the model is not accurately representing the data generating process beyond the sample mean.
  • We could check the residuals and see the same thing - the residuals seem bimodally distributed
# Check residuals plots
ppc_error_hist(y = CO2$uptake,
         yrep = posterior_predictions[1:4,])

Stated differently - in 4,000 posterior draws, there was no instance where the estimate of conc was <= 0. We are 99% sure the estimate for conc is between 0.009 and 0.026

  • How might we further investigate the object we just fit?
  • Here is the model we just fit from a frequentist perspective:
plot(CO2$conc, CO2$uptake, main = "Conc by Uptake") 
# add the line of best fit using least squares estimate
abline(lm(uptake ~ conc, 
          data=CO2),col="red")

Exploring model results from Bayesian perspective

  • Since we used a Bayesian approach with MCMC, We just found a range of reasonable values for the parameter estimates (the posterior). How might we view the full range of results?

  • We can extract the MCMC chains from the fit object into a dataframe, then plot all of them to understand what the results of our model looks like.

posterior1 <- as.data.frame(fit1)
names(posterior1)[1] <- "intercept"
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(CO2, aes(conc,uptake)) + 
  geom_point() + 
  geom_abline(data = posterior1,
              color='red',alpha=0.01,
              aes(slope = conc,
              intercept=intercept)
              )

  • How well does this model fit the data?
  • Where is it a good fit, or a bad fit?

Model evaluation: Residuals

  • How familiar are you with the concept of residual analysis to analyze model fit?
  • We can calculate and view the residuals. For a good model fit, what should the distribution of the residuals be?
  • First we must calculate an expected value based on our model, then we can calculate the difference (the residual).
# Get predictions for each observation
fit1_pred <- posterior_linpred(fit1)

Predicting New Values

  • We use the posterior_predict function to predict new values. First, generate the data we want to make predictions on, then we can make draws from the posterior.
# Check distribution
summary(CO2$conc)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##      95     175     350     435     675    1000
# Create a sequence
conc <- seq(from = 95,to = 1000,by = 15)
length(conc)
## [1] 61
# Establish data frame
df_fit2 <- data.frame(conc)
# make posterior predictions according to the model
temp_preds <- posterior_predict(fit2,newdata = df_fit2)
str(temp_preds)
##  'ppd' num [1:4000, 1:61] 25.01 12.48 9.81 17.24 13.45 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ : NULL
##   ..$ : chr [1:61] "1" "2" "3" "4" ...
  • Now we have a 4000 by 61 matrix, which corresponds to the 61 concentration values we just put into the model!
  • How can we summarize these results? Remember, you can try to either summarize the whole distribution, or just a summary statistic from the distribution. A reasonable choice would be to get the median value and 95% certainty interval for each concentration.
df_fit2$pred_50 <- apply(temp_preds,2,median)
df_fit2$pred_25 <- apply(temp_preds,2,quantile,probs=0.25)
df_fit2$pred_75 <- apply(temp_preds,2,quantile,probs=0.75)
# Create a plot of the center and 75% density interval
ggplot(CO2,aes(conc,uptake)) +
  geom_point() + 
  geom_pointrange(data=df_fit2, color='red', alpha=0.3,
                  aes(y=pred_50,ymin=pred_25,ymax=pred_75,x=conc))

Model Comparison: LOO

  • One way to compare two models fit on the same data after adding a parameter is by using an approximation to leave-one-out cross-validation. There is a loo function available to accomplish this. This is the currently recommended method in rstanarm for model comparisons. It can be time and resource intensive for larger models, so use the cores= argument if you have multicore available.
  • loo stands for leave one out - ‘Pareto smoothed importance-sampling leave-one-out cross-validation (PSIS-LOO)’. This is fairly complex - check this link for more info: https://mc-stan.org/loo/articles/loo2-example.html

And check these papers:

  • Vehtari, A., Gelman, A., and Gabry, J. (2017). Practical Bayesian model evaluation using leave-one-out cross-validation and WAIC. Statistics and Computing. 27(5), 1413–1432. :10.1007/s11222-016-9696-4. Links: published | arXiv preprint.
  • Vehtari, A., Simpson, D., Gelman, A., Yao, Y., and Gabry, J. (2019). Pareto smoothed importance sampling. arXiv preprint arXiv:1507.04544.
library(loo)
# calculate loo and compare
loo0 <- loo(fit0, 
            cores=1) # increase cores argument if you can
loo1 <- loo(fit1)
loo2 <- loo(fit2)
loo_compare(loo0,loo1)
##      elpd_diff se_diff
## fit1   0.0       0.0  
## fit0 -10.1       4.8
loo_compare(loo1,loo2)
##      elpd_diff se_diff
## fit2  0.0       0.0   
## fit1 -5.4       3.5
# compare all
loo_compare(loo0,loo1,loo2)
##      elpd_diff se_diff
## fit2   0.0       0.0  
## fit1  -5.4       3.5  
## fit0 -15.5       5.6

The model with the lowest LOO information criterion is the ‘best fit’ to the data. The standard error of the difference gives us an idea of if that difference is substantial. Fit2 is the best, though the difference between fit1 and fit2 is only ~1.5 standard deviations (5.5/3.5).

Confounding

  • What is Confounding?
  • Ice cream consumption and shark attacks
    • the distortion in an estimated association due to the effect of another variable
    • Confounding is present if there is any meaningful difference between the crude and adjusted estimates.
  • How do I address confounding in the model?

Question: Do you think there is any confounding in this current model, perhaps due to plant type? Fit a model with type added in, and examine the results to tell me if the relationship between treatment and uptake was confounded by type.

MLR with interactions

  • What about effect modification, also called interaction?

  • This is where the association between a predictor and the outcome depends on values of another predictor

    • if the effect of one variable differs or varies across the levels of the other variable
    • x modifies z and z modifies x

  • A simple example would be the effect of birth control and fertility. The relationship between taking birth control pills and fertility would be different for men and women.

  • We put interaction terms into the model explicitly as shown below

Creating a graphical representation of our results

  • As an exercise, I want you to generate a dataframe with a range of predictor values, then visualize the results from model 6. You will need to examine the model components, then create a dataframe that has variation across the relevant variables. I will help you get started with the dataframe creation:
# Use expand.grid to generate the cartesian product of these values
df_mod6 <- 
  expand.grid(conc=seq(100,1000,25),
            Type=c('Quebec','Mississippi'),
            Treatment=c('nonchilled','chilled'))
# make posterior predictions according to the model
temp_preds3 <- posterior_predict(fit6,newdata = df_mod6)
str(temp_preds3)
##  'ppd' num [1:4000, 1:148] 17.6 29 21.5 27 24.5 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ : NULL
##   ..$ : chr [1:148] "1" "2" "3" "4" ...
# Create graphical summary of results
df_mod6$pred_50 <- apply(temp_preds3,2,median)
df_mod6$pred_25 <- apply(temp_preds3,2,quantile,probs=0.25)
df_mod6$pred_75 <- apply(temp_preds3,2,quantile,probs=0.75)
# Create a plot of the center and 75% density interval
ggplot(df_mod6, aes(y=pred_50,ymin=pred_25,ymax=pred_75,x=conc)) + 
  geom_pointrange(color='red', alpha=0.5) +
  facet_grid(Type~Treatment)

  • The posterior_predict() function is prediction (and uncertainty) about individual values

  • Conversely, the posterior_linpred() function is prediction of the expected value (the mean of the linear predictors)

Question: Alter your code above to use the posterior_linpred() instead of posterior_predict() to see the difference in the uncertainty estimates.

Answer Using linpred

# Use expand.grid to generate the cartesian product of these values
df_mod6 <- 
  expand.grid(conc=seq(100,1000,25),
            Type=c('Quebec','Mississippi'),
            Treatment=c('nonchilled','chilled'))
# make posterior predictions according to the model
temp_preds3 <- posterior_linpred(fit6,newdata = df_mod6)
str(temp_preds3)
##  num [1:4000, 1:148] 25.3 24.9 25.4 24.1 22.8 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ iterations: NULL
##   ..$           : chr [1:148] "1" "2" "3" "4" ...
# Create graphical summary of results
df_mod6$pred_50 <- apply(temp_preds3,2,median)
df_mod6$pred_25 <- apply(temp_preds3,2,quantile,probs=0.25)
df_mod6$pred_75 <- apply(temp_preds3,2,quantile,probs=0.75)
# Create a plot of the center and 75% density interval
ggplot(df_mod6, aes(y=pred_50,ymin=pred_25,ymax=pred_75,x=conc)) + 
  geom_pointrange(color='red', alpha=0.5) +
  facet_grid(Type~Treatment)

Regression diagnostics

  • Rstanarm estimates the posterior using a Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm called Hamiltonian Monte Carlo. The details of this algorithm are beyond the scope of this course, however, I will give some practical advice on how to interpret the results found in the GUI shiny app that comes with STAN.
# launch_shinystan(fit6)

Glossary

fit <- stan_glm(y~x,data) general linear regression with MCMC
y ~ x1 + x2 + I(x3*3) formula object
summary(fit) summary of fit object
expand.grid() expand all combinations
plot(fit) regression diagnostic plots
posterior_linpred() get predictions for the expected value posterior_predict() get predictions for the individuals loo(fit) calculate leave one out
